Of course, this is a quartic, so the rational root theorem doesn't really help us here.  We might try guessing some integer roots, and recalling our multiplication facts.  I note that $34$ is divisible by $2$ but not by any other perfect square.  So, let’s try $\pm 1$, and see if either of those works:
\begin{align*}
\left(1\right)^4 + \left(1\right)^4 &= 1+1 = 2 \text {!}\\ 2^4 + 0^4 &= 16 + 0 = 16 \text {!}\\ (-1)^4 + (-1)^4 &= 1+1 = 2 \text {!}\\ -2^4 + 0^4 &= -16 + 0 = -16 \text {!} \end{align*}
So neither $1, -1, 2,$ or $-2$ are roots ... but $35$ is divisible by $7^2$.  So, I should try $\pm 1$, $\pm 7,$ and $\pm 35$ (right?):
\begin{align*}
1^4+(2-1)^4 = 1+(2-1)^4 &= 1 + 1 = 2 \text {!}\\ -1^4+(2+1)^4 &= 1+(2+1)^4 = 1+81 = 82 &= \text{no}\\ 7^4 + (2-7)^4 &= 2401+10000 = 12401 \text{ ?} \\
-7^4 + (2-7)^4 &= -2401+10000 = 7599 \text{ ?} \\
35^4 +(2-35)^4 &= 150062500+75639 \text{ ?}
\end{align*}
I'll just say that there are no integer integer solutions.  So, we need to distinguish these by swapping out polynomials with $2-x$ for $x$, to see if we get complex roots:
\begin{align*}
(-1)^4 + (2-(-1))^4 = (-1)^4+(2+1)^4 &= 1+81=82 \text{ ?}\\
2^4 + (2-2)^4 = 2^4 + 0^4 &= 16+0 = 16 \text{ ?}
\end{align*}
So the roots are complex.  They'll be of the form $a+bi$ and $a-bi$, and their product will be real, i.e., $a^2+b^2$.  Let's tryPutting myself first.
\begin{align}
(a+bi)^4 &= a+bi \\
(a-bi)^4 &= a-bi
\end{align}
Whose sum is exactly $34$, which is real ... OK.  That $a^2+b^2 = 17$, so obviously all the values of $(a, b)$ are $(1,\pm 4)$ or $(2 \pm \sqrt3, \pm 2 \sqrt3)$ or $(\pm 4, \pm 1)$.
So the solutions are $1 \pm4i, 2 \pm \sqrt3 \pm 2\sqrt3 i, 4 \pm i, -4 \pm i$.
